In computational geomechanics, consider an inverse problem for parameter identification in small-strain linear elasticity. An array of displacement sensors provides observations modeled by $d = F(m) + \epsilon$, where $d \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ is the observed displacement vector, $F(m) \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ is the forward model mapping the parameter field $m \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ (for example, a discretized Young’s modulus field) to predicted displacements, and $\epsilon \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ is the measurement error. Assume the errors $\epsilon_{i}$ are independent and identically distributed according to a Student’s $t$ distribution with degrees of freedom $
u > 0$ and scale $s > 0$, whose probability density for a scalar residual $r$ is
$$
p(r \,|\, 
u, s) =  rac{\Gamma\!\left( rac{
